    "glossary.retention": "Money the client holds back from each payment until the work is finished and accepted, as security.",
    "glossary.retention_example": "On a 100,000 invoice with 5% retention, 5,000 is withheld and released at handover.",
    "glossary.variance": "The gap between what you planned to spend or earn and what actually happened. Positive or negative.",
    "glossary.variance_example": "Budget 80,000, actual 86,000, variance is -6,000 (over budget).",
    "glossary.committed": "Cost you have already promised through a signed order or contract, even if no invoice has arrived yet.",
    "glossary.committed_example": "A subcontract is signed for 40,000, so 40,000 is committed before any invoice.",
    "glossary.forecast": "Your best current estimate of the final cost, based on what is spent, committed, and still to come.",
    "glossary.forecast_example": "Spent 30,000 plus a remaining estimate of 50,000 gives a forecast of 80,000.",
    "glossary.payable": "Money you owe to suppliers and subcontractors for work or goods already received.",
    "glossary.payable_example": "A delivered material invoice for 12,000 not yet paid sits in payables.",
    "glossary.receivable": "Money owed to you by the client for work you have invoiced but not yet been paid for.",
    "glossary.receivable_example": "A submitted application for 60,000 awaiting payment is a receivable.",
    "glossary.cpi": "Cost efficiency: the value of work done divided by what it cost. Above 1 is under budget, below 1 is over (cost performance index).",
    "glossary.cpi_example": "90,000 of work done for 100,000 spent gives a CPI of 0.90 (over budget).",
    "glossary.spi": "Schedule efficiency: the value of work done divided by the value you planned by now. Above 1 is ahead (schedule performance index).",
    "glossary.spi_example": "Done 90,000 against a planned 100,000 gives an SPI of 0.90 (behind plan).",
    "glossary.evm": "A method that compares planned value, actual cost, and the value of work really completed to show cost and schedule health (earned value management).",
    "glossary.evm_example": "Planned 100k, spent 110k, earned 95k means you are over cost and behind schedule.",
    "glossary.escrow": "Funds held by a neutral third party and released only when agreed conditions are met.",
    "glossary.escrow_example": "A deposit is held in escrow until both sides sign the handover certificate.",
    "glossary.unit_rate": "The price for one unit of a work item, before multiplying by quantity (unit price).",
    "glossary.unit_rate_example": "45 per m2 of plaster times 200 m2 gives a line total of 9,000.",
    "glossary.price_matrix": "A table of rates that vary by attributes such as region, supplier, or tier, used to pick the right price automatically.",
    "glossary.price_matrix_example": "The same item costs 45 in one region and 52 in another via the price matrix.",
    "glossary.takeoff": "Measuring quantities (lengths, areas, counts) from drawings or models to feed the estimate (quantity takeoff).",
    "glossary.takeoff_example": "Counting 24 doors on a floor plan is a takeoff of 24 units.",
    "glossary.assembly": "A reusable recipe that bundles several cost items into one priced unit, like a wall build-up.",
    "glossary.assembly_example": "A concrete wall assembly bundles concrete, formwork, and rebar into one m2 rate.",
    "glossary.din276": "The German cost-classification standard that groups building costs into cost groups (Kostengruppen).",
    "glossary.nrm": "The UK measurement and cost-classification rules for estimates and bills of quantities (New Rules of Measurement).",
    "glossary.gaeb": "The German electronic exchange format for tenders and bills of quantities, used to send and receive priced work items.",
    "glossary.masterformat": "The North American standard that organises construction work into numbered divisions and sections.",
    "glossary.float": "How long an activity can slip without delaying the project finish (slack).",
    "glossary.float_example": "An activity with 5 days of float can start up to 5 days late with no overall delay.",
    "glossary.makespan": "The total time from the first activity start to the last activity finish across the whole plan.",
    "glossary.makespan_example": "Start on day 0, last finish on day 120, makespan is 120 days.",
    "glossary.crew_flow": "Keeping a crew moving steadily from one location to the next without gaps or clashes (work continuity).",
    "glossary.crew_flow_example": "The tiling crew flows floor by floor with no idle days between them.",
    "glossary.lod": "How detailed and reliable a model element is, from rough placeholder to construction-ready (level of development).",
    "glossary.ids": "A machine-readable rulebook stating exactly which properties a model must carry to be accepted (information delivery specification).",
    "glossary.cobie": "A structured handover spreadsheet of asset data (spaces, equipment, warranties) for the building operator.",
    "glossary.clearance": "The required free gap between elements or around equipment for access, safety, or install.",
    "glossary.clearance_example": "A valve needs 600 mm clearance for maintenance access.",
    "glossary.penetration": "A hole or sleeve through a wall, floor, or beam for a pipe, duct, or cable.",
    "glossary.penetration_example": "A duct passing through a fire wall is a penetration that must be fire-stopped.",
    "glossary.set_a_b": "The two element groups compared against each other in a clash test (clash set A vs set B).",
    "glossary.set_a_b_example": "Set A is the ductwork, set B is the structure; the test finds where they collide.",
    "glossary.datum": "A fixed reference point or level that all measurements are taken from.",
    "glossary.datum_example": "Finished floor level is the datum that heights on the drawing are measured from.",
    "glossary.coordinate_system": "The shared origin and axes that place every model in the same real-world position.",
    "glossary.coordinate_system_example": "Two models align only when they use the same coordinate system and origin.",
    "glossary.anchor_drift": "When models slowly fall out of alignment because their shared reference point has moved or been reset.",
    "glossary.anchor_drift_example": "A re-exported model lands 2 m off because of anchor drift in its origin.",
    "glossary.suitability_code": "A short status code on a document showing how far it can be trusted and what it may be used for.",
    "glossary.suitability_code_example": "Code S2 means for information, not yet approved to build from.",
    "glossary.wip_shared_published": "The three states a document moves through: private work in progress, shared with the team, then published as approved.",
    "glossary.wip_shared_published_example": "A drawing goes from work in progress to shared for review, then published for construction.",
    "glossary.noc": "A formal letter confirming an authority or party has no objection to the work proceeding (no objection certificate).",
    "glossary.capa": "The actions taken to fix a problem and stop it happening again (corrective and preventive action).",
    "glossary.capa_example": "After a recurring defect, the CAPA is a process change plus a check step.",
    "glossary.jsa": "A task-by-task breakdown that identifies hazards and controls before work starts (job safety analysis).",
    "glossary.ppe": "The protective gear a worker must wear for a task, such as a helmet, gloves, or harness (personal protective equipment).",
    "glossary.ncr": "A formal record that something does not meet the specification and must be resolved (non-conformance report).",
    "glossary.snag": "A small defect found during inspection that needs fixing before handover (punch-list item).",
    "glossary.snag_example": "A scratched door noted at inspection is a snag to fix before sign-off.",
    "glossary.spa": "The binding contract that sets the price and terms for buying or selling a property or asset (sale and purchase agreement).",
