    "qms.sign_as_me": "Sign as me",
    "qms.sign_as_me_hint": "You will sign this inspection as yourself in the selected role.",
    "qms.sign_as_role": "Sign as role",
  "qms.intro_title": "One quality chain, not five silos",
  "qms.intro_body": "Run the full ISO 9001 quality chain in one place: ITP plans define hold and witness points, Inspections sign them off, failed checks raise NCRs, NCRs with cost impact escalate to a Variation and feed the Cost of Poor Quality rollup, Punch items track close-out and Audits cover the management system. Pick a project, then work the tabs left to right.",
  "qms.intro_more": "Pick a project, then work the tabs left to right. **ITP Plans** define the inspection and test plan with hold and witness points; activate a plan and open it to sequence hold points and link each control point to a BOQ position, CSI section, drawing or BIM element. **Inspections** record sign-offs against those points. **NCRs** capture defects: open an NCR to assign corrective actions, verify them, and close it out. **Punch List** tracks snags to close-out, and **Audits** cover internal, external and supplier ISO 9001 audits with ratings.\n\nNCRs with a cost impact escalate against a real Variation Order (created first in Variations) and feed the Cost of Poor Quality rollup shown on the NCRs tab. You can export an audit-ready compliance dossier per ITP plan as CSV.\n\n**Getting the most out of it:**\n- Link ITP control points to specs and BOQ positions so the compliance export proves coverage.\n- Watch the Cost of Poor Quality tile to see what rework is really costing.",
    "tendering.addendum.acknowledge": "Acknowledge",
    "tendering.addendum.acknowledge_as": "Acknowledge as:",
    "tendering.addendum.acknowledged_toast": "Acknowledgement recorded",
    "tendering.leveling.excluded_currency": "{{count}} bid(s) excluded: quoted in a different currency than the package ({{currency}}). Leveling never blends currencies; re-quote or FX-convert them first.",
  "tendering.intro_title": "Take a priced BOQ to market and back",
  "tendering.intro_body": "Build bid packages straight from a project BOQ, issue them to subcontractors, and compare offers side by side through Draft, Issued, Collecting, Evaluating and Awarded. Awarding a winner writes the agreed rates back to the BOQ and drafts a purchase order in Procurement, which is what sets this apart from the subcontractor-package flow in Bid Management.",
  "tendering.intro_more": "Create a tender package from a source BOQ, give it a name and scope, then issue it. Each package moves through Draft, Issued, Collecting, Evaluating and Awarded. Open a package to add and compare bids side by side, with the comparison chart showing each bidder against the budget. Three sub-tabs on the package handle the detail: bids and comparison, addenda for mid-tender clarifications, and a leveling matrix for a line by line normalization. An award recommendation flags the suggested winner and warns when a low bid looks suspicious.\n\nAward the winning bid and the platform runs the full transaction: it writes the agreed rates back to the BOQ, marks the package awarded, accepts the winning bid, rejects the rest, and drafts a purchase order in Procurement. That rate write-back and PO are what set this apart from Bid Management.\n\n**Getting the most out of it:**\n- Build the package from a finished BOQ so the rates you get back land on real positions.\n- Use the leveling matrix before awarding, since headline totals can hide scope gaps.\n- Read the recommendation warnings, since the lowest number is not always the safe award.",
    "dashboard.greet_afternoon": "Good afternoon",
    "dashboard.greet_evening": "Good evening",
    "dashboard.greet_morning": "Good morning",
    "dashboard.greet_night": "Welcome back",
    "governance.title": "Governance",
    "governance.subtitle": "Roles & permissions, approval routes, and validation rules, in one place.",
    "governance.tabs": "Governance sections",
    "governance.tab_permissions": "Permissions",
    "governance.tab_approvals": "Approval Routes",
    "governance.tab_validation": "Validation Rules",
  "governance.intro_title": "Set who can do what, and what gets checked",
  "governance.intro_body": "One admin home for three platform controls behind tabs: Permissions sets which role can do what, Approval Routes defines who signs off on RFIs, submittals, change requests and other records, and Validation Rules picks which standards (DIN 276, NRM, GAEB, BOQ quality) a project is checked against. What you set here drives the sign-off badges and validation checks the rest of the modules enforce.",
  "governance.intro_more": "Governance is one admin home with three tabs, and the URL remembers which tab you are on so a link reopens it. **Permissions** is a role-by-permission matrix where you set which role can do what across the platform. **Approval Routes** defines who signs off on records such as RFIs, submittals and change requests, in the order you choose. **Validation Rules** picks which standards a project is checked against, such as DIN 276, NRM, GAEB and BOQ quality.\n\nWhat you set here drives the rest of the app: the permission matrix decides what users can reach, approval routes power the multi-step sign-off badges you see on submittals and other records, and the chosen rule sets are what Validation enforces. Roles tie back to User Management, and every change is recorded in the Audit Log.\n\n**Getting the most out of it:**\n- Set approval routes before issuing records so sign-off runs as a tracked chain, not ad hoc.\n- Match each project's validation rules to its region and standard so checks are relevant.",
    "sidebar.admin_grid.governance": "Governance",
